BST 270 individual project: Bad Drivers

William Nickols

willnickols@g.harvard.edu

Motivations and Reproducibility

This repository reproduces the figures from FiveThirtyEights Dear Mona, Which State Has The Worst Drivers?. Doing so will utilize data from the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (2009, 2012) and National Association of Insurance Commissioners (2010, 2011).

Setup

The package can be installed as described in the README:

if (!require("devtools", quietly = TRUE))
    install.packages("devtools")
    
devtools::install_github('WillNickols/bst270-project', dependencies = TRUE)

The following code loads the required packages and reads the data in from this packages source.

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(dplyr))
library(bst270)

dataset <- read.csv(system.file(package="bst270","extdata","bad-drivers.csv"))

Reproducing Plots

Figure 1: Distracted drivers

The following code reproduces the first figure from the article. It divides the number of fatal collisions per billion miles into those with distracted drivers and those without distracted drivers and plots a stacked bar plot.

# Create a data frame with the number of fatal collisions for
# nondistracted and distracted drivers.
fig1_df <- dataset %>%
    mutate(nondistracted = Number.of.drivers.involved.in.fatal.collisions.per.billion.miles * 
               (Percentage.Of.Drivers.Involved.In.Fatal.Collisions.Who.Were.Not.Distracted / 100),
           distracted = Number.of.drivers.involved.in.fatal.collisions.per.billion.miles *  
               (1 - Percentage.Of.Drivers.Involved.In.Fatal.Collisions.Who.Were.Not.Distracted / 100),
           State = factor(State, rev(State))) %>%
    select(State, nondistracted, distracted) %>%
    reshape2::melt(id.vars = "State") %>%
    mutate(variable = case_when(variable == 'distracted' ~ "TOTAL COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES",
                                variable == 'nondistracted' ~ "NON-DISTRACTED COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES")) %>%
    mutate(variable = factor(variable, levels = c("TOTAL COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES",
                                                  "NON-DISTRACTED COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES")))

# Reproduce figure 1 using a stacked bar plot
ggplot(fig1_df, aes(x = State, y = value, fill = variable)) + 
    geom_bar(position = "stack", stat = "identity") + 
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("NON-DISTRACTED COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES" = "#f6b900", 
                                "TOTAL COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES" = "#f2dfa8")) + 
    ggtitle('Drivers Involved in Fatal Collisions\nWho Were Not Distracted') + 
    theme(
        axis.title = element_blank(),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.position = 'top', 
        legend.direction = 'vertical',
        panel.grid.major.y = element_line(color = "darkgray"),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank()
    ) + 
    coord_flip()

Figure 2: Drivers without previous accidents

The following code reproduces the second figure from the article. It divides the number of fatal collisions per billion miles into those with a driver who had been in a previous accident and those without a driver who had been in a previous accident.

fig2_df <- dataset %>%
    mutate(new = Number.of.drivers.involved.in.fatal.collisions.per.billion.miles * 
               (Percentage.Of.Drivers.Involved.In.Fatal.Collisions.Who.Had.Not.Been.Involved.In.Any.Previous.Accidents / 100),
           old = Number.of.drivers.involved.in.fatal.collisions.per.billion.miles *  
               (1 - Percentage.Of.Drivers.Involved.In.Fatal.Collisions.Who.Had.Not.Been.Involved.In.Any.Previous.Accidents / 100),
           State = factor(State, rev(State))) %>%
    select(State, new, old) %>%
    reshape2::melt(id.vars = "State") %>%
    mutate(variable = case_when(variable == 'old' ~ "TOTAL COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES",
                                variable == 'new' ~ "COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES OF DRIVERS W/O PREVIOUS ACCDIENTS")) %>%
    mutate(variable = factor(variable, levels = c("TOTAL COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES",
                                                  "COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES OF DRIVERS W/O PREVIOUS ACCDIENTS")))

ggplot(fig2_df, aes(x = State, y = value, fill = variable)) + 
    geom_bar(position = "stack", stat = "identity") + 
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES OF DRIVERS W/O PREVIOUS ACCDIENTS" = "#44ab43", 
                                "TOTAL COLLISIONS PER BILLION MILES" = "#bcdbbc")) + 
    ggtitle('Drivers Involved in Fatal Collisions Who Had\nNot Been Involved In Any Previoius Accidents') + 
    theme(
        axis.title = element_blank(),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.position = 'top', 
        legend.direction = 'vertical',
        panel.grid.major.y = element_line(color = "darkgray"),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank()
    ) + 
    coord_flip()

Limitations and Biases

The author mentions the following biases in the original data sources used:

The federal government doesnt track hate crimes systematically (agencies report to the FBI voluntarily), and the Southern Poverty Law Center uses media accounts and peoples self-reports to assess the situation. Moreover, FBI hate crimes data for 2016 wont be released for another several months, and the Southern Poverty Law Center didnt collect data before the 2016 election. However, both data sources are publicly available and easy to navigate, which means theyre some of the best we have.

But they also have biases baked in.

The FBI Uniform Crime Reporting Program collects hate crime data from law enforcement agencies. But because the data is submitted voluntarily, its unclear how comprehensive the data set is. We dont have data from Hawaii, for instance. Moreover, the UCR Program collects data on only prosecutable hate crimes, which make up a fraction of hate incidents (which includes non-prosecutable offenses, such as circulation of white nationalist recruitment materials on college campuses).

On the other hand, the Southern Poverty Law Center data which comes from a combination of curated media accounts and self-reported form entries includes both hate crimes and non-prosecutable hate incidents. Moreover, heightened news coverage of hate incidents after the election may have encouraged people to report incidents that they would not have otherwise reported. This is called awareness bias a trend that is well-established in epidemiology, environmental health and other fields of research that frequently use self-reported data.
